            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Michelle Fong\u2019s story is woven into the very fabric of San Francisco\u2019s Inner Richmond district. The daughter of Hong Kong immigrants who ran a small but beloved noodle shop on Clement Street, she grew up breathing in the scent of saltwater fog and simmering broth. Her childhood was a library of stories\u2014tales from her parents of a life across the ocean, and the daily dramas of the neighborhood regulars who treated their restaurant as a second home. This immersion in narrative sparked her desire to tell stories, leading her to pursue a journalism degree at San Francisco State University.\n\nGraduating in the late 90s, Michelle entered a field on the verge of digital disruption. She found brief success as a reporter for a local paper, but grew disillusioned with the relentless 24-hour news cycle and the shift toward clickbait. The turning point came during an assignment covering the closure of a century-old community center. While others focused on the immediate controversy, Michelle was captivated by the boxes of fading photographs and brittle documents being discarded. She realized she cared more about preserving the past than chasing the fleeting present.\n\nThis epiphany prompted a career pivot. She retrained in information science and found her true calling as a digital archivist. Now, as a senior archivist for a major cultural institution downtown, she spends her days safeguarding the city\u2019s memory\u2014digitizing fragile histories, from Gold Rush-era letters to the records of a defunct tech startup. Her work is a quiet rebellion against the ephemeral nature of the digital age.\n\nHer daily routine is a bedrock of stability. She takes the 5R Fulton MUNI from her tidy apartment, a few blocks from where she grew up, to her SoMa office. Evenings are often spent with her now-retired father, sharing a meal and listening to his familiar stories. Her social life is a small, tight-knit circle of friends, many known since childhood, with whom she shares weekend dim sum and hikes at Land\u2019s End.\n\nMichelle\u2019s dream is to launch a personal project: a comprehensive digital archive of the Sunset and Richmond districts\u2019 Cantonese-speaking communities. She wants to preserve the stories of the grocers, the tailors, and the noodle shop owners like her parents, ensuring their history is not lost to gentrification and time. For Michelle, archiving isn't just a profession; it\u2019s an act of love for the city that raised her."
